                    <h5>
                        Climate change:
                    </h5>

                    <p>
                        Climate change causes increase in temperature levels and decrease in rainfall levels, which will potentially cause longer drier periods. If there is decline in rainwater levels, obviously water storage would decrease and cause water scarcity. These climate changes also increase the chance of bushfires. Bushfires are very directly involved with water storage and water quality.
                        The majority of water catchments and water reservoirs are surrounded by natural land. This natural bushland keeps water cleaner. but if bushfires occur, there can be change in the water quality due to the residues released by the bush fires, which not only makes water quality worse, rather makes it worse and unfit for human consumption.
                    </p>

                    <h5>
                        Why does it matter?
                    </h5>

                    <p>
                        Melbournians collectively consume 980 million litres of water per day. With Melbourne’s population growing and climate change making rainfall less reliable, these factors affect the fact that how much water can make it to storages from rainfall. We cannot rely on only rainwater.
                        It is very high time to look into alternatives and also save and use water very efficiently. Everyone needs to be responsible and do their part.
                        It is said that an average person can use 155 litres of water per day, by using water efficiently and be a part of this beautiful efficient water usage campaign.<br />
